{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514705"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12356"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12356"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.41,0.19,0.35,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"628"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11162"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 22-year-old woman presents with rapid onset of a pruritic red rash. She reports three prior similar episodes in the last six months, all of which have self-resolved within hours. This current episode started approximately four hours ago at her workplace as a hairdresser. The pruritus is so severe that she was unable to continue working. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 104/72 mmHg pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The rash is readily evident on her trunk and legs - multiple erythematous annular patches and plaques with central clearing (Image). The lesions are palpable on examination. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bullous pemphigoid","Urticaria","Granuloma annulare","Erythema multiforme","Angioedema"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has\u003Cstrong\u003E urticaria\u003C/strong\u003E, which typically presents as itchy spots or rashes, which last a few minutes or hours and resolves leaving no marks on the skin. The key features that suggest this diagnosis include the rapid onset of the rash, the pruritic nature of the lesions, the fact that the patient has had similar episodes in the past, and the presence of erythematous annular patches and plaques with central clearing. These are all characteristic of urticaria. Common risk factors for the development of urticaria include female gender, medications, occupations with high contact with latex or high skin friction, insect bites and stings. This is mainly a case of acute urticaria which typically last less than 6 weeks. Chronic urticaria is characterised by hives that last longer than six weeks. The cause of chronic urticaria is often unknown, but it may be related to an underlying autoimmune disorder, infection, or other underlying conditions such as thyroid dysfunction or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E is an immunobullous condition which usually occurs over the age of 65\u00a0years with tense blisters and erosion. It may present acutely or be insidious in onset. The lesions are most commonly on the limbs and trunk. It can be idiopathic or be drug-induced. It does not improve spontaneously within 24h.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranuloma annulare \u003C/strong\u003Eis a benign skin condition that causes raised, red or skin-colored bumps that form a ring or arc shape on the skin. The bumps are usually small and can appear on any part of the body, but are most common on the hands and feet. The cause of granuloma annulare is not well understood, but it is not an allergic reaction and is not contagious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnset of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E is usually sudden in an otherwise healthy individual. Characteristic features include target lesions - a central red area surrounded by a pale halo and a red ring. In the majority of cases erythema multiforme is precipitated by HSV1 infection, but also can be caused by medications or other infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Eangioedema,\u003C/strong\u003E the patient presents with swelling that develops over hours and resolves after days. It causes well demarcated swelling of the subcutaneous tissues and mucous membranes Tingling, tightness and pain are the main symptoms, associated with oedema. Specific sites will be examined to make sure they are not involved e.g. lips, tongue, periorbital area, throat and airway, abdomen and genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urticaria, also known as hives, is a skin rash characterised by raised, red, itchy welts.","Acute urticaria typically resolves within hours to days and is often triggered by allergens or stress. It is self-limiting in most cases."],"references":["Kanani A, Betschel SD, Warrington R. Urticaria and angioedema. Allergy Asthma Clin Immunol. 2018 Sep 12;14(Suppl 2):59. doi: 10.1186/s13223-018-0288-z. PMID: 30263036; PMCID: PMC6157046. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30263036/","Kolkhir P, Gim\u00e9nez-Arnau AM, Kulthanan K, Peter J, Metz M, Maurer M. Urticaria. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2022 Sep 15;8(1):61. doi: 10.1038/s41572-022-00389-z. PMID: 36109590. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36109590/","Poonawalla T, Kelly B. Urticaria : a review. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2009;10(1):9-21. doi: 10.2165/0128071-200910010-00002. Erratum in: Am J Clin Dermatol. 2012 Jun 1;13(3):215. PMID: 19170406. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19170406/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18910"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18910"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/62a4344f-bbb5-484a-99fe-115380790ecf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/62a4344f-bbb5-484a-99fe-115380790ecf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":390}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T18:22:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T18:22:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105992"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":